Graph-theoretic assessment (Pearl-school SCM discipline):

1) Selection f and the “non-computable from G alone” retreat
- In Pearl’s framework, a graph G encodes parent sets; it never determines the structural functions F nor exogenous terms U. So “f is not computable from G alone” is tautological under-specification, not an uncomputability result.
- h23 countermodel (memory determinization): Augment the model with a memory state M_t and action A_t such that
  A_t = g(Ω_t, M_t), Ω_{t+1} = T(Ω_t, A_t), M_{t+1} = h(Ω_t, M_t).
  For any path-selection rule f over outgoing neighbors N+(Ω_t), one can choose g,h and an initial M_0 so the induced trajectory equals the “free” selection. Hence, conditional on (G, g, h, M_0), evolution is deterministic. The proponent’s retreat concedes exactly this: “not from G alone” just means “you omitted the policy state.” It is underdetermination (missing parents), not Turing-uncomputability.
- If V and all out-degrees are finite, f is table-computable. Claiming genuine uncomputability requires a reduction (e.g., Halting) showing no Turing machine can compute f even given full mechanism; none is provided.

2) “Royal Purple” edge creation and DAG mutation
- Pearl’s theorems are proved relative to a fixed G. Adding an edge e* produces a new graph G′ with new d-separation, new Markov class, new admissible adjustment sets, and revised structural functions (child gains a parent). You cannot transport results proved in G to G′ without reproof. Calling this “extending the DAG” is methodologically invalid; it is model replacement.
- Acyclicity risk: a locally added edge can close a directed cycle unless the agent has global reachability knowledge. Even if acyclicity is preserved, all conditional independences may change.
- The “|0> XOR |1> → O” description is a mechanism change (at least two new parents into O with a Boolean gate), not “instantiating a single edge.” Formally, you introduce a new v-structure and must rewrite F_O.

3) Free will as path choice vs SCM interventions
- In SCMs, “choice” is a policy variable A with parents in the agent (memory, beliefs, preferences) and arrows into future states. Modeling choice as unmodeled nondeterministic path selection collapses to h23: a hidden parent set makes it deterministic once included.

4) Identity/uniqueness claims are not graph-invariant
- “Irreducible/non-substitutable node” is not definable from the unlabeled DAG up to isomorphism. Picking out a specific vertex by biography is metadata, not a structural property of G. Any such claim requires a graph-invariant criterion; none is given.

Methodological prescription: Fix a single DAG G, add explicit agent nodes (M_t, A_t), supply structural functions and exogenous distributions, or else index distinct phases (pre-/post-”Royal Purple”) as separate models {G^e} with selection nodes S_e governing mechanism change; then re-establish all identifiability/independence results. Without this, the core claims are not theorems but moving-target assertions.

